\description{
Fits the unsupervised tree boosting procedure of Awaya and Ma (2024).
Marginal trees are fitted first, followed by dependence trees. The fitted
ensemble represents a probability distribution on a rectangular support.
}
\section{Fitting stages}{

The procedure first fits up to \code{max_marginal_trees} univariate trees for
each variable. It then fits up to \code{max_dependence_trees} multivariate trees
to the remaining dependence structure. These arguments are upper bounds;
adaptive stopping can end a stage earlier.
}

\section{Scale-specific learning rate}{

For a node \eqn{A} in the normalized unit cube, the learning rate is
\deqn{c(A) = c_0 (1 - \log_2[\mathrm{vol}(A)])^{-\gamma}.}
Thus \code{c0} determines the global update size. When \code{gamma = 0}, every node
uses \code{c0}. When \code{gamma > 0}, smaller-volume nodes receive smaller updates,
which imposes stronger shrinkage on local structure.
}

\section{Adaptive stopping}{

If \code{early_stop = NULL}, all observations fit each candidate tree and no
adaptive stopping is applied. With \code{early_stop = c(threshold, window)}, each
candidate tree is fitted to a random 90 percent subset of the current
residuals and evaluated by its average log density on the held-out 10
percent. A stage ends when the mean of the most recent \code{window} held-out
scores is strictly below \code{threshold}. The candidate that triggers stopping
is recorded in \code{heldout_diagnostics} with \code{accepted = FALSE} but is not added
to the ensemble.
\code{c(0, 50)} is the paper-oriented setting; the implementation uses a strict
comparison with zero, whereas the paper describes non-positive improvement.
}

\section{Support and tied observations}{

Data are transformed from \code{Omega} to the unit cube before fitting. If
\code{Omega = NULL}, the range after optional tie perturbation is expanded by 10
percent on each side. Set \code{add_noise = TRUE} when a continuous distribution
is assumed and ties are technical artifacts such as rounding. Set it to
\code{FALSE} when perturbing ties would be inappropriate.
}

\section{Split prior}{

The default \code{prior_split_prob = 0.9} follows the archived implementation and
public experiment code. Setting \code{prior_split_prob = 0.5} corresponds to the
constant split prior implied by the 0.5 stopping probability reported in
Appendix C of Awaya and Ma (2024). Larger values favor splitting before the
data-dependent candidate likelihoods are incorporated.
}

\section{Reproducibility and progress}{

Tree construction is stochastic even when \code{add_noise = FALSE}, and adaptive
stopping also draws random fitting subsets. Call \code{\link[=set.seed]{set.seed()}} before every
fit that must be reproducible. Fitting is silent by default; set
\code{progress = "stage"} for stage-level messages. Elapsed time is stored in the
result and can be inspected with \code{\link[=print]{print()}} or \code{\link[=summary]{summary()}}. Exact equality
across operating systems has not been established.
}

